                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">A map on Yafeng’s website showed its distribution and a list of available drugs to purchase.</span>
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        U.S. government
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="39.0">Yet the sales pitches left little doubt that the firm knew its activities were illegal. Yafeng websites utilized familiar terms assuring U.S. and Mexican drug users and traffickers of the company’s skill at smuggling illegal narcotics overseas, according to the House report and U.S. investigators. The company touted its use of “hidden food bags,” a method in which drugs are concealed in shipments labeled as food products. Ads promised “strong safety delivery to Mexico, USA” with “packaging made to measure” to “guarantee” that illicit chemicals would elude border inspections, documents show.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="40"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size04 right out02 wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
